    content: `
      <img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F74272db3-836b-4f40-a798-1e8f00fc2fce_806x806.png" alt="The Obesity Olympics Paradox" class="article-hero-img">
      <p>It's been 53 days since the end of the Paris 2024 Olympics at the time of writing. We won 18 gold medals this year, breaking the record of 17 that we achieved at Tokyo and at Athens in 2004. We finished 4th in gold medals and 5th in total medals — an amazing achievement considering we are the <a href="https://www.worldometers.info/world-population/population-by-country/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">55th country by population</a>.</p>
      <p>I found that there is a <a href="https://www.medalspercapita.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">website dedicated</a> to medals per capita. I sadly found out that we are only 9th and 10th for total and gold medals per capita respectively, where the leading countries were Grenada and Dominica. Fun fact: The country with the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/San_Marino_at_the_2020_Summer_Olympics" target="_blank" rel="noopener">lowest ever population</a> to win a medal is San Marino during the 2020 Olympics — with only 34,000 people, they won three medals.</p>
      <p>I was discussing this with a friend, trying to make the argument that Australia is the best sporting and athletic nation in the world. He noted that six of the top 10 average crowd leagues are from the US, and that in men's football the Socceroos often struggle to even make the FIFA World Cup. I conceded we weren't the best, but I still believe we're right in the conversation.</p>
      <p>I didn't think about this for a few days, until I was reminded of another set of Australian statistics — our obesity rates.</p>
      <h2>Australia's Obesity Rates</h2>
      <p>According to the <a href="https://data.worldobesity.org/rankings/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">World Obesity Federation</a>, over 30% of Australian adults are obese, and over 15% of children are considered obese. If you expand to include those considered overweight, the numbers <a href="https://www.aihw.gov.au/reports/overweight-obesity/overweight-and-obesity/contents/summary" target="_blank" rel="noopener">more than double</a> for adults to 66%, while children jump to 26%.</p>
      <p>On one hand, we are one of the best sporting nations on the planet — since 2018, <a href="https://australianoftheyear.org.au/recipients" target="_blank" rel="noopener">four Young Australians of the Year</a> have been professional athletes. On the other hand, almost two-thirds of adults and over a quarter of kids are overweight or obese. What kind of mass psychology is creating this Obesity-Olympics paradox?</p>
      <h2>The Paradox Around The Globe</h2>
      <p>The US has won the total medal and gold medal tally for the last four Olympics and seven of the last eight. Yet a staggering 41% of US adults are obese — fourth in the world for countries over a million people. Let's look at China, which also reached 40 gold medals this year and has a strong culture around sport. Yet only 8% of the Chinese adult population is considered obese — five times less than the US.</p>
      <h2>Obesity Rates & GDP Per Capita</h2>
      <p>Logic would have it that higher GDP per capita means more disposable income for food and therefore higher obesity. But Japan has under 6% obesity with a $45,000 GDP per capita. Singapore, with the second-highest GDP per capita on the planet, has only 14% obesity. Tuvalu has one of the highest obesity rates at 65% but only $5,000 GDP per capita. Being rich or poor doesn't seem to determine whether a country will have high obesity rates.</p>
      <h2>Geography</h2>
      <p>Unsurprisingly — the food they eat. Residents of Asian countries are often consuming healthier alternatives like rice- or noodle-based dishes. Asia produces 90% of the world's rice. The Mediterranean diet is another such example. However, American-style foods are practically available everywhere in all Western countries, yet not every country with a McDonald's has high obesity rates. Geography explains some but not all.</p>
      <h2>Urbanisation</h2>
      <p>Urbanisation has a lot to say in this conversation. The lifestyle of an urban environment promotes sedentary living — cars, public transport, and office-based jobs are all big contributing factors. Urban environments are also well-populated with fast food chains that are cheap, convenient, and often cheaper than healthier alternatives. Again, though, Japan has the biggest urban area in the world in Tokyo, yet has very low obesity rates. So what's left?</p>
      <p><em>→ <a href="article.html?slug=the-obesity-olympics-paradox-part-2" style="color:var(--gold)">Continue to Part 2 →</a></em></p>
    `,
